{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17516922","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17516922"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:48:34+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:48:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12729"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12729","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12729"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.58,0.04,0.08,0.28,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5184"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49301"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5184","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5184"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12729"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34521"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"6132"},{"type":"tags","id":"6153"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8783"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8842"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15683"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49301","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/49301"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 67-year-old woman visits her general practitioner with a three month history of persistent right shoulder pain. The pain is sharp in nature, localised to the top of the shoulder, 7/10 in severity, non radiating and progressively worsening. It is also worse on movement, particularly abduction of the arm. The pain causes difficulty with her daily activities such as brushing her hair, and she has stopped playing tennis because of it. There was no history of trauma. Two weeks prior to this presentation she was given an injection of 1% lidocaine into the joint, but it did not relieve the pain or improve her range of motion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, there is significant pain when the arm is passively abducted at 60-120 degrees of movement, and she is unable to hold up her arm at a 90 degree angle, with the arm dropping to her side.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Rotator cuff tear","Cervical radiculopathy","Calcific tendinitis","Subacromial bursitis","Polymyalgia rheumatica"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERotator cuff tear\u003C/strong\u003E is the correct answer. The patient presents with pain exacerbated by overhead activity/movements of the arm. The symptoms of pain on passive shoulder abduction between 60-120 degrees suggests an impingement of the rotator cuff, and the positive arm drop test narrows down the muscle affected to the supraspinatus muscle. Although there is limited sensitivity and specificity in these specific physical examinations, an ultrasound or MRI should be used to confirm the diagnosis. Non-severe rotator cuff tears are usually treated conservatively with physiotherapy and analgesia,\u003Cem\u003E \u003C/em\u003Ebut surgery is indicated in severe/complete muscle tears with significant functional impairment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECervical radiculopathy\u003C/strong\u003E is usually caused by spondylosis or a herniated disc in the cervical spine, where there is compression of the cervical nerves. This can result in neck/shoulder/arm pain that radiates distally and may be exacerbated by specific neck movements or positions. There can also be paraesthesia in the dermatomes supplied by the compressed cervical nerve. However in this case, the pain does not radiate and is replicated with passive shoulder abduction, which is not consistent with this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECalcific tendinitis\u003C/strong\u003E is an inflammatory condition associated with deposition of calcium phosphate crystals. Although it can also manifest with pain on overhead activity/movements of the arm, there would not be any pain elicited on passive movement, any weakness as seen in the positive drop arm test. In addition, calcific tendinitis is effectively treated with intra-articular lidocaine injection. Thus this diagnosis is unlikely to be causing the patient\u2019s symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESubacromial bursitis\u003C/strong\u003E refers to inflammation of the subacromial bursa located below the acromion and above the supraspinatus muscle. This condition is usually due to chronic repetitive movements of the shoulder, especially in overhead arm movements, resulting in associated pain when performing these movement. However, this would not cause any weakness on the drop arm test. If subacromial bursitis is untreated, it can progress to subacromial impingement and adhesive capsulitis (frozen shoulder).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPolymyalgia rheumatica (PMR) \u003C/strong\u003Etypically presents in women \u0026gt;50-years-old, resulting in shoulder pain and prolonged morning stiffness that lasts \u0026gt;45 minutes. However, this condition is usually bilateral and diffuse, and can be associated with neck or hip pain.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Positive drop arm test \u2013 Inability to hold arm up at 90 degrees of abduction, indicates a rupture of the supraspinatus muscle."],"references":["Sambandam SN, Khanna V, Gul A, Mounasamy V. Rotator cuff tears: An evidence based approach. World journal of orthopedics. 2015 Dec 12;6(11):902."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34521"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12729"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34521","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/34521"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-07-27T10:57:25+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-22T09:35:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5184"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49301"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"34","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/34"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb4","name":"Orthopaedics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4974","links":{"self":"https://app.emedic